## Code Quality Patterns

### Early Validation Pattern

**Always validate inputs before accessing properties or calling methods:**
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Early validation
function processChannel(channel: Channel | null | undefined): boolean {
    if (!channel) return false; // Validate first
    
    // Now safe to access properties
    if (channel.isDM()) return false;
    if (!channel.guild_id) return false;
    
    return PermissionStore.can(PermissionsBits.VIEW_CHANNEL, channel);
}
```

**Rules:**
- Check for null/undefined at the start of functions
- Validate array bounds before accessing elements
- Check object existence before calling methods
- Use early returns to avoid deep nesting

### Consolidated Condition Checks

**Combine related conditions into single if statements:**
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Consolidated check
function canUse(channel: Channel | null | undefined): boolean {
    if (!channel) return false; // Early return for validation
    
    // Combine related checks
    if (!isSupportedChannel(channel) || (channel.guild_id && !PermissionStore.can(...)))
        return false;
    
    return true;
}
```

**Why:**
- Better performance (single evaluation)
- Cleaner code (less repetition)
- Easier to understand (logical grouping)

### Handler Extraction Pattern

**Extract event handlers instead of using inline functions:**
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Extracted handler
function Component() {
    const handleClick = () => {
        if (!channelId) return;
        toggleGallery(channelId);
    };
    
    return <Button onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

**Benefits:**
- Easier debugging (can set breakpoints)
- Better performance (function created once)
- Removes redundant checks (disabled prop handles UI state)
- Cleaner code organization

### Array Access Safety

**Always validate arrays and indices before access:**
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Safe array access
function getItem(items: Item[], index: number): Item | null {
    if (!items || items.length === 0 || index < 0 || index >= items.length)
        return null;
    
    return items[index];
}
```

### Missing Dependencies in useStateFromStores

**NEVER omit the dependencies array when the mapper depends on reactive values:**
```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Missing dependency
const channel = useStateFromStores(
    [ChannelStore],
    () => ChannelStore.getChannel(channelId) // channelId not in deps!
);

// ✅ GOOD - Include dependencies
const channel = useStateFromStores(
    [ChannelStore],
    () => channelId ? ChannelStore.getChannel(channelId) : null,
    [channelId] // Dependencies array
);
```

